overview: There are several things to consider before, during, and after getting a divorce. This brochure explains what a divorce is and the requirements needed to start the process. It briefly covers useful legal terms related to a divorce and common issues that affect the spouses and their family.
name: Learn about Divorce Law in Hawaii
description: Information about Divorce Law in Hawaii

overview: After a divorce is filed by one spouse, the other spouse has a chance to respond through a court filing called an "answer." This brochure covers what an answer is, why you should file one, how to fill it out, and  what to expect after you complete this step in the divorce process.
name: What to do if you Receive Divorce Papers from your Spouse
description: Information about what you should do if you receive Divorce papers from your spouse

overview:
Pre-decree relief means any type of temporary order (of protection, custody, restraining order, etc) that happens BEFORE the divorce or paternity judgment is made final.

Post-decree relief means any type of temporary order (of protection, custody, restraining order, etc) that happens AFTER the divorce or paternity judgement is made final.

The instructions are to be used as a guide for completing either the pre-decree relief or post-decree relief form.
name: Instructions and Forms for Pre-Decree and Post-Decree Motion Filings
description: Instructions and Forms for pre-decree and post-decree relief motion filings, requests for all types of relief before and after a divorce or paternity judgment have been made final.

overview: This brochure provides guidance on how to ask the court for a fee waiver so you don't have to pay to file your case.
name: How to Request a Fee Waiver in Family Court
description: How to request a fee waiver to file a case in family court.

overview: As a part of all divorce cases, your spouse must be properly served (delivered) a copy of the divorce forms that you filed at court so that s/he knows that you are starting the divorce process. If you cannot locate your spouse or do not know where your spouse currently is, Family Court still needs you to do your best to locate your missing spouse so that the missing spouse has the chance to agree or disagree with the divorce. This brochure offers tips on how to search for and find your spouse.
name: How to Search for a Missing Spouse
description: How to search for a missing spouse when you want to get a divorce but are not in contact with your spouse and/or do no know where to locate your spouse.

overview: As a part of all divorce cases, your spouse must be properly served (delivered) a copy of the divorce forms that you filed at court so that s/he knows that you are starting the divorce process. This brochure explains what service means, how you should prepare to serve your spouse, how to correctly file the documents with the court clerk and serve your spouse, and what happens after your spouse is served.
name: How to Serve Your Spouse on the Same Island
description: Information on how to serve your spouse when you want to start a divorce if s/he is on the same island as you.

overview: A divorce usually takes several months and may take longer if there are disagreements about child custody or support, dvision of money and other issues. This brochure talks about mediation, another option to think about before you go to court.
name: Mediation of Divorce Cases
description: Steps to get a divorce and reach an agreement without using lawyers or going to court.

overview: If you have a family court order, judgment, or custody determination from another state, you can register that order with the Family Court in Hawaii. This brochure provides the steps and forms necessary to properly register your order.

name: Self-Help Form: Divorce without Children, Oahu - Part 1
description: Interactive interview used to complete the first set of forms for starting the divorce process without children.

description: Interactive interview used to complete the second set of forms for the divorce process without children.

name: Self-Help Form: Answer for Complaint for Divorce
description: Interactive interivew used to complete the complete a short answer or response to the divorce papers you received from your spouse.

name: Self-Help Form: Motion and Declaration for Pre Decree Relief
description: Interactive interview used to complete the form asking for any type of temporary order (of protection, custody, restraining order, etc) that happens BEFORE the divorce or paternity (custody/child support) judgment is made final.

name: Self-Help Form: Appearance and Waiver
description: Use this interactive interview if you have received a Complaint for Divorce, agree with your spouse (Plaintiff) on the matters of the divorce, and signed the Divorce Decree. Completing and filing the Appearance and Waiver means that you agree that the court may grant the divorce without you going to court.

name: Self-Help Form: Asset and Debt
description: Use this interactive interview if you would like to complete the Asset and Debt Statement for a Divorce case in Family Court of the First Circuit (Oahu).

name: Self-Help Form: Ex Parte Motion and Declaration to Advance or Expedite Hearing
description: Use this interactive interview to assist you in completing either 1) A motion requesting that the court move your hearing to an earlier date (Advance Hearing) OR 2) A motion requesting that the court accelerate the time it normally takes to receive and consider a response (Expedite Hearing).

name: Self-Help Form: Motion and Affidavit to Waive Filing Fees - Oahu (First Circuit)
description: Use this interactive interview to complete the form asking the court to waive your court filing fees because you cannot afford to pay such costs. This could be used for Family Court cases where there are filing fees including Divorce, Paternity, Adoption and Guardianship.

name: Self-Help Form: Motion and Declaration for Post Decree Relief
description: Interactive interview used to complete the form asking for any type of temporary order (of protection, custody, restraining order, etc) that happens AFTER the divorce or paternity (custody/child support) judgment is made final.

name: Self-Help Form: Motion and Declaration for Post Decree Relief - Maui (Second Circuit)
description: Interactive interview used to complete the form asking for any type of temporary order (of protection, custody, restraining order, etc) that happens AFTER the divorce or paternity (custody/child support) judgment is made final.

name: Self-Help Form: Motion for Service by Mail
description: Interactive interview used to complete a Motion for Service by Mail and Affidavit; Order for Service by Mail required in a Divorce case if your spouse lives on a different island. name: Self-Help Form: Proposed Parenting Plan

eligibilityInformation: ALSC provides free legal services to eligible clients determined by income eligibility and case eligibility. Generally, you will be eligible if your income does not exceed 125% of the Federal Poverty Income Guidelines for Alaska.  Alaskans over the age of 60 are usually provided aid regardless of income.  The kind of issue must also be wihin their priorities.
name: Alaska Legal Services Corporation
description: Helps low income Alaskans address civil legal issues affecting their families, homes, incomes, jobs and access to vital services such as health care and utilities.  Staff attorneys and volunteer lawyers who donate their time provide legal assistance.   Additionally, ALSC offers self-help resources to help individuals independently navigate the court system.  ALSC's legal experts publish information on a variety of issues, offer community legal education, and refer clients to other social services as needed.

The kind of issue must also be wihin their priorities.
name: Alaska Network on Domestic Violence and Sexual Assault
description: ANDVSA's Legal Program provides case representation and information and referral to victims of domestic violence, sexual assault and stalking who need help with civil matters including family law, housing law, and consumer issues.  ANDSVA works with trained legal advocates statewide who refer cases to them.  They use both staff attorneys and volunteer attorneys to handle cases.

address: www.alaskamediators.org/directory
name: Professional Mediators of Alaska
description:
Professional Mediators of Alaska is a nonprofit organization formed in 2015 to support the mediation profession and encourage its use in Alaska as an alternative form of conflict resolution. 

Mediation offers an alternative way for people in conflict to reach a resolution that preserves their control over the outcome.  It is a voluntary, confidential process where parties meet with a neutral third party, the mediator, who facilitates a negotiation. Mediation minimizes the investment of time and cost involved in resolving a dispute, and can occur before a lawsuit is ever filed or anytime between a complaint and trial.                                                                     The goals and objectives of Professional Mediators of Alaska are to:

Educate the public about the benefits of mediation for the resolution of family,  business, and community conflicts
Provide ongoing training opportunities for professional mediators
Promote the profession of mediation
Encourage collaboration among mediators and develop a statewide network of professional mediators
Promote adherence to standards of practice among professional mediators

address: www.alaskacollaborative.org/find-a-professional

name: Alaska Association of Collaborative Professionals
description: AACP is an association of lawyers, financial professionals and counselors dedicated to offering clients a confidential, out-of-court dignified approach to handle divorce, custody, modification and other family maters through the use of the collaborative law approach.   For the Collaborative Law process to work, both clients must be willing to resolve the dispute and to work toward that end, which includes fully disclosing all relevant information.  If there has been physical or substance abuse or criminal activity, Collaborative Law may not be an appropriate choice.  Please consult with an attorney trained in Collaborative Law to determine what is appropriate in your situation.

Las víctimas pueden representarse de manera efectiva durante el proceso en el cual piden una orden de protección contra la violencia doméstica en sus casos y pueden obtener la protección y ayuda disponibles que les dan las leyes de protección contra la violencia doméstica.

If someone has committed domestic violence against you and you want to understand what protection is available, see How to Represent Yourself in Alaska's Domestic Violence Protective Order Process, PUB-22.

Child Custody And Visitation Mediation

This brochure provides information about the Alaska Court System's Child Custody and Visitation Mediation Program for parents who have a divorce, dissolution, child custody, or visitation case pending in court,
or who want to modify an existing
court order or decree.

In this program, experienced mediators assist parents to work out agreements acceptable to both parents. Parents maintain control
of the decisions throughout the process. The parenting plan that is developed usually becomes part of the divorce, dissolution, or custody agreement.

name: Domestic Relations Trials - Understanding the Two Options
description: This brochure from the Alaska Court System describes the two different types of trials - informal and formal - to resolve domestic relations cases (actions for divorce, property division, parenting arrangements, and child support, as well as modifications). You will need to choose the type of trial that you think is best for your case.  Learn about the two options.

name: How to Serve a Summon in a Civil Lawsuit
description: This brochure from the Alaska Court System provides information about serving a summons, a required document to notify the other side in a court case about a lawsuit.  It describes the methods allowed as well as different considerations for each method.

name:
Child Custody and Visitation Investigations, 
Information For Parents

name: How to Calculate Child Support Under Civil Rule 90.3
description: This booklet from the Alaska Court System provides information to calculate child support for cases of dissolution, divorce, and custody between unmarried parents.  It explains how to calculate annual adjusted income including allowable deductions and how to plug that information into the formulas for different parenting arrangements.

name: Information About CSSD
description: The Child Support Services Division (CSSD) is the state agency responsible for enforcing child support orders. In order for CSSD to enforce a support order, a parent must apply for CSSD services. Also, if the custodial parent is receiving public assistance, or the child is in state custody, CSSD will open a case automatically.

description: list of local school district websites for school calendars for Alaska Superior Court locations

name: Ending Your Marriage - Filing for Divorce or Dissolution
description: To end a marriage, one or both spouses need to file a document in court.  Choosing the document depends on whether they agree on all issues:  ending the marriage how to divide marital property and debts, the parenting plan for minor children and child support.  If they agree it is called a dissolution case and if they disagree it is called a divorce.  A dissolution happens after both spouses file a petiton together stating how they want to address all issues.  The court holds a short hearing to go over the agreement and makes sure it meets all of the legal requirements.  A divorce happens after a longer process with paperwork from both sides.  The divorce is granted either by an agreement of the spouses or a judge's decision after a trial where each side argues their positions and provides supporting evidence.

name: Filing for Child Custody by Unmarried Parents
description: Parents who are not married to each other file a custody case to figure out a parenting plan that includes how decisions will be made about the  children (legal custody), what living arrangments and schedule they will have to be with each parent (physical custody) and the child support amount. A custody order is based on what arrangement is in the children’s best interests.

name: Responding to a Complaint Served on You
description: If one spouse files a complaint for divorce, the other spouse needs to file a response which is called an answer within 20 days to participate in the divorce case.  If the other spouse does not file an answer, the spouse who started the divorce can ask the court to enter a default judgment which means the case will move ahead with the court considering only their requests.

name: Serving the Other Side
description: Every time someone files a document in a court case, he/she must give a copy to the other side which is called service of process.  This is so everyone knows everything that is going on in a court case and what information goes to the judge.  There are strict rules about how to serve different kinds of documents.  It is very important to understand how to properly serve documents to the opposing party (or their lawyer if represented). Not doing it correctly can make a case grind to a halt.

name: Filing for a Default Judgment When the Other Side Doesn't Answer the Complaint
description: If someone receives a complaint for divorce and does not respond by filing an answer, the person who filed the complaint can ask the court to default the other side.  This means the court will decide the case based only on the information it received in the complaint.

name: Making a Request of the Court - Filing a Motion or an Opposition to a Motion
description: A motion is the paper you file to ask a judge to make a ruling or take some other action.  Motion practice is the three-step process to ask the judge to order something in the case. First, the moving party, i.e. the person who is asking for a court order, files a motion, asking the court to order something specific. Second, the other party files a response or opposition. Third, the moving party can reply to the opposition.  After hearing from both sides, the judge will issue an order granting or denying the motion.

name: Understanding the Trial Options - Informal or Formal
description: If your case is not able to resolve by an agreement and you need a judge to decide the issues, you will need to choose the type of trial that you think is best after understanding the options. Two different types of trials - informal and formal - are available to resolve cases involving divorce, property and debt division, parenting arrangements, and child support, as well as modifications. Both people in the case can choose to have an informal trial where the judge will decide the issues in the divorce case.  There are special rules designed to make the trial process easier for people who are representing themselves in an informal trial.  The judge asks all of the questions so the spouses do not ask each other questions during the trial.  Both spouses can present whatever evidence they think is important for the judge to consider D100 do not need to follow the Rules of Evidence.  The spouses cannot make objections to testimony or to the evidence the other side introduces.  After the informal trial where the judge hears testimony and considers the evidence, the judge will make a decision. This is different than a formal trial where each side presents their side of the case by making arguments and presenting evidence, including witness testimony and exhibits.  The Rules of Evidence are in effect, and each side can make objections when the Rules of Evidence are violated.  There is a specific way that questioning witnesses happens, including the type of questions that are allowed.  Before deciding the type of trial you want, it is important to understand the options.

name: Formal Trials
description: A formal trial is the way a trial traditionally happens.  Both sides present their arguments about what they want the judge to order and introduce supporting evidence.  There is a specific order to how the trial happens, including how witnesses are questioned and evidence introduced.  Everyone needs to follow the Rules of Evidence and understand the process of questioning witnesses including direct exam, cross-exam and redirect exam.  After hearing all of the evidence, the judge will make a decision.

name: Getting Ready for a Hearing or Trial
description:
In a family law case, a trial is the court proceeding when each side presents their arguments and supporting evidence for what each wants the court to order. When the trial is over, the judge issues final orders and the case is over. For example, in a divorce with property and children involved, the trial will result in final orders that grant the divorce, divide the marital property and debts, issue a parenting plan and a child support order.
A hearing is a court proceeding where one or a few issues are decided usually on a temporary basis before the trial. Hearing are shorter than trials and may be as short as 15 minutes or as long as 2-3 hours. For example, a parent may file a motion for a temporary parenting plan for their child. The judge may hold a hearing and ask both parents to present their argument on what the child's living schedule should be until trial when the final parenting plan is ordered. After hearing from both parents and considering any evidence presented, the judge may order a temporary parenting plan. Hearings also occur when someone files a motion to modify a parenting plan or child support after a final judgment has been entered.  It is helpful to prepare for a trial or hearing to be able to communicate what you want and present your evidence.

name: Finishing the Case
description: The case is not over until the judge issues the final paperwork.  These documents are called Findings of Fact and Conclusions of Law and Final Decree and Judgment.  If there are children of the marriage, there will also be a parenting plan or custody and visitation plan and a child support order.  Sometimes the judge announces the decision at the end of the trial in the courtroom but the decision needs to be put in writing.  It is important to understand who is responsible to write up the final documents.  Usually the judge will write them up when people are representing themselves in the case.  If there are lawyers involved, the judge may ask one of the lawyers to write up the final documents according to what the judge said in court.  Sometimes the judge may ask one of the people representing themselves to write up the documents.  Before you leave the courtroom after the trial, make sure you understand what you are responsible to do, both to follow the order and to know if you are supposed to write up the final documents.

name: After You Get Your Final Judgment or Order
description: When the case is over you will get your final documents which may be called Findings of Fact and Conclusions of Law and Final Decree and Judgment.  Usually these documents states the final decision about the issues. For a divorce case, the final documents will end the marriage, include how the marital property and debts will be divided, and restore a maiden name if requested.  In a divorce with children and a custody case between unmarried parents, the final documents will state what the parenting arrangement will be and who will pay a specific amount of child support starting on a specific date.  It is important to understand these documents because they state what you and the other side are responsible to do.  Sometimes one or both people in the case are unhappy with the final decision in the case.  If you want to file something to change the outcome, there are different possible options with different deadlines depending on the reason you are not satisfied with the order.

name: Enforcing Your Order
description: Sometimes one side in the case does not follow the court order.  To get that person to comply, there are different options.  Generally the first step is to file a written request to the opposing party asking them to do what the order says by a specific date. Hopefully he/she will follow the order and you won't need to go back to court.  If he or she does not cooperate, the next step is to let the court know by filing a motion. The type of motion depends on the specifics of what the court ordered and what the opposing party did or didn't do about following the order. Your motion usually asks the court to issue an order telling the opposing party to do something specific.  There is a specific process to collect money that is ordered to be paid.

name: Collecting Money Owed to You
description: A court case ends with the judge's written decision that states one or both parties' responsibilities to carry out the order. In a family law case, this final decision is called the decree and judgment. If you have a document called a judgment that says someone owes you money, you are called the judgment creditor. The person who owes the money to you is called the judgment debtor.  If the debtor does not voluntarily pay the amount owed, there is a process to try to get the money called execution.

name: Modifying Child Custody or Child Support
description: After a court issues a parenting plan or custody order, there could be a change of circumstances by one or both parents or the children that require modifying the parenting plan.  Also, the child support order may need to be modified if there is a change in the parenting plan or a change in one or both parents' incomes.  Parents can always modify the parenting plan by agreement but the court needs to find a change of circumstances to order a modification.  The court needs to modify the child support order if warranted.

name: Registering Foreign (Out-State) Orders
description: If you want the Alaska courts or Alaska police to take action in Alaska on the court order you have from another state, you generally must register the foreign order in Alaska. Some people register a foreign order simply to be able to enforce it; other people register a foreign order as the first step to modify act.

name: Child Support
description: Both the court and the Child Support Service Division (CSSD) have the authority to issue child support orders.  However, the child support orders come about in different ways.  The court must issue a child support order when it decides a parenting plan ( the custody and visitation arrangement)  for a child in a case involving divorce, dissolution, or custody between unmarried parents.  The CSSD issues an order when one parent requests child support because the parents have split up and the parent taking care of the child(ren) wants the other parent to pay support for the child.  Sometimes a parent will have a CSSD support order and then file a custody case in court later.  If the court issues a child support order that is different from the CSSD order, the court’s child support order takes priority and replaces the CSSD order.

name: Parenting Plans and Custody
description:
A custody order or "parenting plan" usually includes the following based on what arrangement is in the child’s best interests:
•Parenting Schedule (physical custody): sets out specific days and times for children to be with each parent, including logistics about the exdchange.
•Decision Making (legal custody) : sets out how the parents will make decisions about the children's health, education and religious upbringing.
•Financial Matters: identifies which parent will apply for PFDs, what will happen to those funds, and which parent will claim children for tax purposes in which years.
•Child Support: requires that children have adequate financial support as required under Civil Rule 90.3.•Health Insurance: states how children get health insurance, who will pay and how will parentsl handle uninsured costs.

name: Parenting Coordination
description: Parenting coordination is a process used when parents continue to disagree about the court-ordered parenting plan. Parenting coordination can be helpful when parents have a history of filing many motions to modify because of continued problems. Instead of coming back to court to file more motions, the Parenting Coordinator works with the parents in an out-of-court process to resolve disputes quickly.

name: Paternity
description: Establishing paternity means legally determining the father of a child. Once established, the father's name can be placed on the child's birth certificate and he has legal responsibility for the child. Disestablishing paternity is legally un-naming a man as the child's father.  Alaska law requires that the husband's name be entered on the birth certificate as the child's father if the mother was married at conception, during the pregnancy or at the time of the child's birth.  If  the husband is not the father of a child born or conceived during the marriage, it is important to disesatblish paternity and establish paternity of the correct father.  There are different ways to deal with paternity issues, including in a divorce case.

name: Genetic (DNA) Testing
description: Genetic testing, more commonly called "DNA testing," shows whether someone is the parent of a child. A DNA sample is collected using a swab, similar to a Q-Tip inside the cheek to pick up cells. Samples are collected from the mother, the child and the person who may be the father. The testing is painless and the whole process takes about 15 minutes. Once all the samples have been collected, the result is ready within about 3 weeks.  In a court case to deal with paternity, you can submit your genetic testing results as evidence.

name: Changing Birth Certificates
description: After the paternity issue is resolved and the correct father is established, you can correct the birth certificate.  The Bureau of Vital Statitics is the agency that has forms that deal with birth certificates.

name: Dividing Marital Property and Debt
description: When a couple ends their marriage through a divorce or dissolution, the court will divide their marital property and debts according to several factors set out in the law.  The goal is for the division to be fair and equitable.

name: Qualified Domestic Relations Orders - Dividing Retirement Accounts in a Divorce or Dissolution
description: QDRO (pronounced "KWADRO") stands for Qualified Domestic Relations Order. QDROs are state court orders issued in divorce or dissolution cases that give retirement benefits to someone other than the plan participant usually the ex-spouse. Under federal law, the retirement plan administrator  determines whether a court order from a divorce or dissolution meets the plan's requirements to pay the benefits.

name: Spousal Support
description: In Alaska, you can request that the court order one spouse to pay the other spouse a specific amount of money called spousal support (alimony).  There are two kinds of spousal support - reorientation and rehabilitation - and both are limited in duration.  Generally, the court prefers to do an unequal division of the marital property and debts than order spousal support which avoids keeping ex-spouses financially connected after the divorce.  Sometimes spousal support is ordered on a temporary basis before trial so that one spouse has enough money to live before the property and debt division is finalized.

name: Uncontested Matters, Agreements and Settlements
description: In a family law case, it is great if the spouses or parents can reach an agreement about the issues.  The agreement can be about all of the issues or just some of them.  The case can start out as an uncontested case which means all issues are agreed when the case is filed.  The case can also start out as contested because the people don't agree or don't know whether they agree, but they later reach an agreement.  The people in the case need to write up the agreement and file it with the court.  The judge will have a hearing to make sure the agreement meets the legal requirements and issue a final order on the agreed issues.

description: This video provides an introduction to the video series on divorce and custody cases for those representing themselves in Alaska.

description: This video describes some methods used by people who already agree or think they can come to an agreement with some help.  These methods are called alternative dispute resolution because they are alternatives to a contested hearing or trial where a judge makes the decision instead of the people in the case.

It also discusses options to include in the plan such as cultural activities, contact with extended family members, transportation considerations, communications methods to keep in touch with children when a parent cannot be with them physically.

description: This video explains the requirement of service or providing the other side with a copy of every document you file in the case.  It also discusses how to fill out the certificate of service showing you served the other side.

name: Appearing in Court From A Distance
description: This video explains how to participate in hearings and trial by telephone, including filing a motion to appear by telephone, planning to send exhibits in advance and how to deal with witnesses.

name: Filing Documents By Mail
description: This video explains how to file documents by mail, including information about serving the documents.

name: Introduction to Hearing and Trial Preparation for Family Law Cases
description: This video provides an overview of the hearing and trial preparation video series for family law cases.

name: Finding Court Forms
description: This video explains where to find online court forms.

name: Representing Yourself
description: This video explains where to find online court forms.

name: Getting Legal Advice
description: This video explains the options for finding a lawyer or representing yourself.

name: The Family Law Self-Help Center
description: This video explains the services of the Alaska Court System Family Law Self-Help Center.

name: How will I know when to be in court?
description: This video explains the scheduling order or notice of hearing that states the date of the trial or hearing.

name: Giving Copies to the Other Side (Certificates of Service)
description: This video explains the requirement of serving the other side with all filed documents and how to fill out the certificate of service.

name: What Documents Do I need to Complete Before My Trial or Hearing?
description: This video explains the required documents to file including their deadlines.

name: Witness List
description: This video explains how to fill out the witness list before the trial.

name: Pre-trial/hearing Brief
description: This video explains how to fill out the pre-trial brief and the hearing brief, including attaching other forms that can help you organize the information.

name: What happens at a hearing or trial?
description: This video explains the order of events at a hearing or trial.

name: What is evidence?
description: This video explains what the court considers evidence:  witness testimony and exhibits (documents, photographs, records, bills, etc.).

name: Opening Statement
description: This video explains what to say in the opening statement.

name: How to Question Witnesses
description: This video explains how the questioning of witnesses work, including direct examination, cross-examination and redirect examination and the types of questions used for each type.

name: Questioning your own witness
description: This video explains how to question your own witnesses during a direct examination.

name: Testifying Yourself
description: This video explains how to provide your own direct testimony when representing yourself in court.

description: This video explains how ask re-direct examination questions for your witnesses after the other side asks cross examination questions.

name: What is a Rebuttal Witness?
description: This video explains what a rebuttal witness is and what to do if a rebuttal witness is needed to testify.

name: Difference Between Testimony and Asking Questions
description: This video explains the difference between presenting testimony and asking a witness questions.

name: Closing Statement
description: This video explains what to say in a closing statement at the end of a trial.

name: Choosing Your Witness
description: This video explains how to choose your witnesses to testify at a hearing or trial.

name: What is an offer of proof?
description: This video discusses an offer of proof for witnesses and why it is a helpful organizing tool to prepare for trial.

name: Preparing your witness
description: This video explains how to prepare your witnesses to testify at a hearing or trial.

name: What to do if your witness won’t come to court?
description: This video discusses options if a key witness says he or she won't come to court, including using a subpoena that requires them to come to court.

name: How do I choose and prepare my exhibits?
description: This video explains how to prepare your exhibits, including selection, how to mark them with stickers and the number of copies to make.

name: How do I introduce exhibits in the courts?
description: This video explains how to introduce exhibits to be considered as evidence during witness testimony, including the specific steps.

name: The Rules of Evidence
description: This video discusses information about the Rules of Evidence, including their purpose.  It also explains the most important things to understand.

name: How do I make objections?
description: This video explains the basics of how to make an objection when the other side violates the rules of evidence during testimony or introducing an exhibit.

name: About the Judge
description: This video discusses the role of the judge and the requirement to be neutral and impartial and what to expect from the judge's actions in the courtroom.  It also explains the prohibition against talking to the judge outside the courtroom.

name: What Happens After the Hearing or Trial is Over?
description: This video explains what happens after the hearing or trial is over and the judge makes a decision.

name: Writing up court orders
description: This video discusses who may be responsible to write up the court order and what to do if you are supposed to write it up.

name: Important: Updating Your Address
description: This video explains why it is important to keep your address updated with the court even after you get your final order.

name: Tips on preparing for your hearing or trial
description: This video discusses the best way to prepare for your hearing or trial, including what to expect and how to prepare your testimony, witnesses and exhibits.

name: Domestic Violence Protective Orders Video - English
description: This video explains how to apply for a domestic violence protective order in an Alaska state court. It discusses how to represent yourself at your hearing for a long-term (one-year) order and how to plan for your safety. It also highlights issues that you need to think about if you have children. For more information about protective orders, please see http://courts.alaska.gov/shc/shcdv.htm. You can also call the Family Law Self-Help Center at (907) 264-0851 (in Anchorage) or toll-free (866) 279-0851 (works in Alaska but from a non-Anchorage phone number).

name: Domestic Violence Protective Orders Video - Español
description: Este video está en Español y explica cómo solicitar una orden de protección de violencia doméstica en la corte del Estado de Alaska. El video explica cómo representarse a usted mismo en la audiencia para una orden de largo plazo (un año) y cómo planear su seguridad. También pone de relieve hechos en los que usted tiene que pensar si tiene niños. Para más información sobre órdenes de protección, por favor lea: "Como Representarse En El Proceso de Una Orden de Protección de Violencia Doméstica de Alaska", PUB-22S . Usted también puede llamar al Centro de Ayuda de Leyes de Familia al (907) 264-0851 (en Anchorage) o llamar gratis al (866) 279-0851 (afuera de Anchorage, pero en Alaska).

name: Domestic Violence Protective Orders Video - Yup'ik
description: Nallunruyuutellrit wall' nelgutkilriit uitarcurlallriit Qanercetaarvegkun ikayungcautiit  This video explains in Yup'ik how to apply for a domestic violence protective order in an Alaska state court. It discusses how to represent yourself at your hearing for a long-term (one-year) order and how to plan for your safety. It also highlights issues that you need to think about if you have children. For more information about protective orders, please read: How to Represent Yourself in Alaska's Domestic Violence Protective Order Process, PUB-22 . You can also call the Family Law Self Help Center at (907) 264-0851 (in Anchorage) or toll-free (866) 279-0851 (outside Anchorage but in Alaska).
